VTell your daughters of this year,
p4
aVhow we woke needing coffee
p5
aVbut discovered instead cadavers strewn about our morning papers,
p6
aVwaterlogged facsimiles of our sisters, spouses, small children.
p7
aVSay to your baby of this year when she asks, as she certainly should,
p8
aVtell her it was too late coming.
p9
aVAdmit even in the year we leased freedom, we didn't own it outright.
p10
aVThere were still laws for every way we used our privates
p11
aVwhile they pawed at the soft folds of us,
p12
aVgrabbed with no concern for consent,
p13
aVno laws made for the men that enforced them.
p14
aVWe were trained to dodge,
p15
aVto wait, to cower and cover,
p16
aVto wait more, still, wait.
p17
aVWe were told to be silent.
p18
aa(lp19
VBut speak to your girls of this wartime,
p20
aVa year preceded by a score of the same,
p21
aVso as in two decades before,
p22
aVwe wiped our eyes,
p23
aVlaced caskets with flags,
p24
aVevacuated the crime scene of the club,
p25
aVcaterwauled in the street,
p26
aVlaid our bodies on the concrete against the outlines of our fallen,
p27
aVcried, "Of course we mattered,"
p28
aVchanted for our disappeared.
p29
aVThe women wept this year.
p30
aVThey did.
p31
aa(lp32
VIn the same year, we were ready.
p33
aVThe year we lost our inhibition and moved with courageous abandon
p34
aVwas also the year we stared down barrels,
p35
aVsang of cranes in skies, ducked and parried,
p36
aVcaught gold in hijab, collected death threats,
p37
aVknew ourselves as patriots,
p38
aVsaid, "We're 35 now, time we settled down and found a running mate,"
p39
aVmade road maps for infant joy, shamed nothing but fear,
p40
aVcalled ourselves fat and meant, of course,
p41
aVimpeccable.
p42
aa(lp43
VThis year, we were women,
p44
aVnot brides or trinkets,
p45
aVnot an off-brand gender,
p46
aVnot a concession, but women.
