aa(lp56
VWhen she asks you of this year,
p57
aVyour daughter, whether your offspring or heir to your triumph,
p58
aVfrom her comforted side of history teetering towards woman,
p59
aVshe will wonder and ask voraciously,
p60
aVthough she cannot fathom your sacrifice,
p61
aVshe will hold your estimation of it holy,
p62
aVcuriously probing, "Where were you?
p63
aVDid you fight? Were you fearful or fearsome?
p64
aVWhat colored the walls of your regret?
p65
aVWhat did you do for women in the year it was time?
p66
aVThis path you made for me, which bones had to break?
p67
aVDid you do enough, and are you OK, momma?
p68
aVAnd are you a hero?"
p69
aVShe will ask the difficult questions.
p70
aa(lp71
VShe will not care about the arc of your brow,
p72
aVthe weight of your clutch.
p73
aVShe will not ask of your mentions.
p74
aVYour daughter, for whom you have already carried so much, wants to know
p75
aVwhat you brought, what gift, what light did you keep from extinction?
p76
aVWhen they came for victims in the night,
p77
aVdid you sleep through it or were you roused?
p78
aVWhat was the cost of staying woke?
p79
aVWhat, in the year we said time's up, what did you do with your privilege?
p80
aVDid you sup on others' squalor?
p81
aVDid you look away or directly into the flame?
p82
aVDid you know your skill or treat it like a liability?
p83
aVWere you fooled by the epithets of "nasty" or "less than"?
p84
aVDid you teach with an open heart or a clenched fist?
p85
aVWhere were you?
